    fullDescription: "Fort McMurray is unlike anywhere else in Alberta. It sits at the confluence of the Athabasca and Clearwater rivers, deep in subarctic boreal country, and serves as the operational capital of the Athabasca oil sands.\n\nThe 2016 Horse River wildfire - nicknamed \"The Beast\" - forced the largest wildfire evacuation in Canadian history, moving about 88,000 people out and destroying roughly 2,400 structures. Whole neighbourhoods, including Beacon Hill, Abasand, and Waterways, have been rebuilt to modern building codes since. Those newer homes sit alongside 1970s and 1980s boom-era subdivisions like Thickwood and Timberlea, workforce condos and apartments, and mobile-home parks.\n\nThe economy revolves around the oil sands. Suncor, Syncrude, and other operators run plants north of town along Highway 63, drawing a fly-in and drive-in workforce and some of the highest household incomes in the province.\n\nThen there is the climate. Wood Buffalo endures among the coldest winters of any sizeable Canadian urban area, with deep -40 C snaps, short summers, and serious wildfire exposure.\n\nMacDonald Island Park, Canada's largest community recreation centre, anchors life here between the river valleys. Fort McMurray sits about 423 km northeast of Edmonton, far enough that you want a crew who understands the north firsthand.",
