    shortDescription: "Nanton is a town in southern Alberta, about 84 kilometres south of Calgary along Highway 2, with a population of 2,214 recorded in the 2021 census. It sits at the foot of the Porcupine Hills on the western prairie, in ranching and grain-farming country. Nanton is best known for the Bomber Command Museum of Canada, home to a restored Avro Lancaster bomber, and for its row of historic wooden grain elevators and antique-lined main street. Long noted for its natural spring water, the town serves as a service stop for the surrounding foothills farms and ranches.",
    fullDescription: "Nanton is a foothills town of about 2,200 people, sitting 84 kilometres south of Calgary where Highway 2 runs along the base of the Porcupine Hills. For its size, Nanton punches far above its weight in landmarks. The Bomber Command Museum of Canada, with its airworthy-condition Avro Lancaster, draws aviation enthusiasts from across the country, while the town's preserved row of wooden grain elevators and its antique-shop-lined main street pull in weekend travellers heading between Calgary and the mountains. Nanton has also long been known for its natural spring water, once bottled and sold as a local point of pride.\n\nNanton sits in the chinook belt, where warm winds pour down off the Porcupine Hills and can lift winter temperatures far above freezing before they crash again overnight. The repeated freeze-thaw cycling that follows is hard on shingles, flashing, and siding, and the open western prairie gives the wind plenty of room to hammer exposed buildings.\n\nThe town's building stock leans older. Around the main street and the grain elevators are heritage storefronts and early-century homes, while newer builds fill in the residential edges. Many properties here are aging character buildings whose roofs and exteriors have taken decades of chinook wind, so they need care from a crew that understands their construction. Beyond the town, ranches and grain farms spread across the foothills toward High River to the north and Claresholm to the south.",
