    fullDescription: "Sundre is a foothills town in the truest sense: it sits on the Red Deer River exactly where the open central Alberta plains begin climbing toward the Rocky Mountains. West of town, the land rises into the West Country, a vast forest reserve laced with campgrounds, fishing streams, and off-highway trails that pulls visitors through Sundre all summer long.\n\nTwo roads meet here and set the pattern of the town. Highway 27 runs east toward Olds and the QE2 corridor, while Highway 22 - the Cowboy Trail - threads north and south through the ranch and foothills country. Along them sit a mix of properties: older homes on mature town lots, newer builds, working farms and ranches, shop buildings, and recreational cabins near the forest edge.\n\nThis close to the mountains, the town sees heavier and wetter snow than the open plains, with spring snow that loads roofs, strong freeze-thaw swings, and wind sliding down off the eastern slopes. Summer still brings central Alberta's hail-bearing thunderstorms, sometimes sharpened against the higher ground.\n\nLocal knowledge counts for a lot in country like this.",
