    fullDescription: "Hanna stands on the wide, open plains of east-central Alberta, where Highways 9 and 36 cross in the heart of the Special Areas. The town was born around 1912 as a Canadian Northern Railway divisional point, and that railway heritage still shapes its grid of streets and its role as the service centre for a huge stretch of farm and ranch country.\n\nLife on this exposed prairie is defined by weather. With little tree cover and no real chinook relief, Hanna sees wind-driven snow, long deep-freeze stretches, and summer thunderstorms that can drop hail across the fields.\n\nThe building stock here rewards local knowledge. You will find early brick storefronts along the old railway main street, postwar bungalows, farmhouses, and working ranch buildings scattered out toward the Hand Hills, the rolling upland southeast of town that hosts the Hand Hills Lake Stampede, one of the oldest stampedes in Canada.\n\nHanna also carries a bigger footprint than its size suggests. It is the hometown of the rock band Nickelback, a point of local pride, and it sits within reach of the Sheerness generating station and the recreation at Fox Lake, all of which keep people and traffic moving through town.\n\nBecause Hanna is remote, dependable scheduling matters.",
