    fullDescription: "Trochu has a backstory unlike almost any other prairie town. In 1903, Armand Trochu and a group of French cavalry officers established the St. Ann Ranch Trading Company on this spot in what is now Kneehill County, and the settlement that grew up around it carried a distinctly French-settler character. That heritage is still visible at the St. Ann Ranch site and celebrated at the Trochu Arboretum and Gardens, an unusual living collection of more than a thousand trees and shrubs on the open plains.\n\nToday Trochu is a small farming community of roughly a thousand residents, about 127 kilometres northeast of Calgary and 192 from Edmonton. It sits just 14 kilometres from Three Hills and within easy reach of the Red Deer River badlands and Drumheller to the southeast. The building stock is a familiar central-Alberta mix: older homes near the original main street, postwar bungalows, newer builds, and farmhouses on the rich black-soil quarters that surround the town.\n\nThe climate here shapes the work as much as anywhere in central Alberta. Trochu sees hail-bearing summer thunderstorms, warm dry stretches, and a full parkland winter with deep cold snaps and pronounced April and October freeze-thaw.",
